{{For|the myth on which the painting is based|Diana and Actaeon}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Titian - Diana and Actaeon - Google Art Project.jpg | title=Diana and Actaeon | artist=Titian | year=1556–1559 | medium=Oil on canvas | height_metric=185 | width_metric=202 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in |city= | museum=[[National Gallery (London)|National Gallery, London]] }}
'''''Diana and Actaeon''''' is a painting by the [[Italian Renaissance]] master [[Titian]], finished in 1556–1559, and is considered amongst Titian's greatest works. It portrays the moment in which the hunter [[Actaeon]] bursts in where the goddess [[Diana (mythology)|Diana]] and her nymphs are bathing. Diana is furious, and will turn Actaeon into a stag, who is then pursued and killed by his own hounds, a scene Titian later painted in his ''[[The Death of Actaeon]]'' ([[National Gallery]]).
Diana is the woman on the right side of the painting. She is wearing a crown with a crescent moon on it and is being covered by the dark skinned woman who may be her servant. The nymphs display a variety of reactions, and a variety of nude poses.
In 2008–2009, the [[National Gallery (London)|National Gallery, London]] and [[National Gallery of Scotland]] successfully campaigned to acquire the painting from the [[Orleans Collection|Bridgewater Collection]] for £50&nbsp;million. As a result, ''Diana and Actaeon'' will remain on display in the UK, and will alternate between the two galleries on five-year terms.
==To 2005== ''Diana and Actaeon'' is part of a series of seven famous canvases, the "poesies", depicting mythological scenes from [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' painted for [[Philip II of Spain]] (after [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor]] had declined Titian's offer to paint them for him).<ref>Brigstocke, 180 and 183-4</ref> The work remained in the Spanish royal collection until 1704, when King [[Philip V of Spain|Philip V]] gave it to the French ambassador. It was soon acquired by [[Philippe II, Duke of Orléans]], nephew of [[Louis XIV]], and Regent of France during the minority of [[Louis XV of France|Louis XV]], for his [[Orleans Collection|collection]], one of the finest ever assembled. After the [[French Revolution]], the [[Orleans collection]] was sold to a [[Brussels]] dealer by [[Louis Philippe II, Duke of Orléans]] in 1791, two years before he was guillotined.<ref>Brigstocke, 11</ref> This dealer then exhibited many pictures from the collection (including the Titians) in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/aug/30/art.celebrity.money|title=The industrial revolution brought Titians and Renoirs to Scotland|first=Ian|last=Jack|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=30 August 2008|accessdate=2008-08-30 | location=London}}</ref>
The largest share of the collection was thus bought in 1798 by the coal-magnate [[Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater]], including this painting, Titian's ''[[Diana and Callisto]]'' (from the same mythological series of seven paintings), eight paintings by [[Poussin]], three [[Raphael]]s and [[Rembrandt]]'s ''Self-Portrait, aged 51''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgalleries.org/index.php/collection/online_az/4:322/results/0/8677/|title=Rembrandt, "Self-Portrait, aged 51" – NGS catalogue entry|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219003336/http://www.nationalgalleries.org/index.php/collection/online_az/4%3A322/results/0/8677/|archivedate=2012-02-19|df=}}</ref>
The third Duke of Bridgewater was probably inspired to buy the paintings by his nephew, [[George Leveson-Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland|Earl Gower]], the ancestor of the Dukes of Sutherland. Certainly, on Bridgewater's death five years after the purchase, he bequeathed the Titians and the rest of the collection to Gower, who put it on display to the public in his [[Bridgewater House, Westminster|London house]] – it has been on public display ever since. On first seeing the collection there, [[William Hazlitt]] wrote "I was staggered when I saw the works&nbsp;... A new sense came upon me, a new heaven and a new Earth stood before me.". On the outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in September 1939, the collection was moved from London to [[Scotland]]. Between 1945–2009, the ''Diana and Actaeon'' and ''Diana and Callisto'' (with other paintings from the collection, known collectively as "the Bridgewater loan" or "the Sutherland Loan"<ref>The loan includes a total of 26 paintings, sixteen from the Orléans Collection. – Brigstocke, 11</ref>) were on long-term display at the National Gallery of Scotland, in Edinburgh. As well as Hazlitt, during their time on public display they have inspired artists such as [[JMW Turner]]<ref>Paul Hills, "Titian's Fire: Pyrotechnics and Representations in Sixteenth-Century Venice", ''Oxford Art Journal'' 2007 30(2), pages 185–204</ref> and [[Lucian Freud]] — Freud described the pair as "simply the most beautiful pictures in the world".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2001/12/22/bafreud22.xml|title=Artists on art: Freud on Titian|first=Lucian|last=Freud|authorlink=Lucian Freud|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=22 December 2001|accessdate=2008-08-30 | location=London}}</ref>
==2008–present== The Sutherland collection has passed by descent to the [[Francis Egerton, 7th Duke of Sutherland|7th Duke of Sutherland]], (most of whose wealth is contained in the paintings collection), but in late August 2008 the 7th Duke announced that he wished to sell some of the collection in order to diversify his assets.<ref>He had previously sold another Titian from the loan — the ''[[Venus Anadyomene (Titian)|Venus Anadyomene]]'' — to the NGS in 2000.</ref> He had offered them as a pair to the British national galleries at £100&nbsp;million (a third of their overall estimated market price) if they could demonstrate, by the end of 2008, the ability to raise that sum — if not, the pair or other paintings from the Bridgewater collection would be put on public [[auction]] early in 2009. Within days of the Duke's decision, the NGS and the [[National Gallery (London)|National Gallery]], London had announced they would combine forces to raise the sum, initially in the form of £50&nbsp;million (or a demonstration that this money could be raised) to purchase ''Diana and Actaeon'' and paid over three years in instalments and then £50&nbsp;million for ''Diana and Callisto'' paid for similarly from 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Bates|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/aug/28/art|title=Art auction: National galleries scramble to keep Titians as duke cashes in|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 August 2008|accessdate=2008-08-28 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/aug/28/art|title=Editorial: In praise of... the Bridgewater loan|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 August 2008|accessdate=2008-08-28 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgalleries.org/aboutus/news/1:171/5879|title=National Galleries of Scotland press release|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219003215/http://www.nationalgalleries.org/aboutus/news/1%3A171/5879|archivedate=2012-02-19|df=}}</ref>
Though the campaign received some criticism for the Duke's motives or (from [[John Tusa]] and [[Nigel Carrington]] of the [[University of the Arts London]]) for distracting from funding art students,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/nov/16/titian-art|title=Arts chiefs warn of harm from Titian crusade|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|work=[[The Observer]]|date=16 November 2008|accessdate=20 November 2008 | location=London}}</ref> it gained press support from both the tabloid and broadsheet print media in the UK<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2008/oct/31/titian-diana-actaeon|title=Enough vulgar Marxism – we must keep Titian's masterpiece|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 October 2008|accessdate=20 November 2008 | location=London | first=Jonathan | last=Jones}}</ref> – imitative nude [[photoshoot]]s of it were featured in both ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' (using the newspaper's ''[[Page 3]]'' models [[photoshop]]ped onto the painting) and ''[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]]'' (including the actor [[Kim Cattrall]] and featured in a piece by [[Andrew Graham-Dixon]] on ''[[The Culture Show]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/11/25/nice-titians-kim-115875-20922362/|title=Nice Titians, Kim|date=25 November 2008|work=[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/article1950277.ece|title=Page 3 girls brush up well|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=20 November 2008}}</ref> On 14 October 2008 the appeal received £1 million from the [[Art Fund]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7667706.stm |title=£1&nbsp;m pledge for Titian masterpiece |accessdate=2008-11-19 |date=14 October 2008 |publisher=[[BBC News]] }}</ref> and on 19 November this was followed by £10 million from the [[National Heritage Memorial Fund]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7737204.stm |title=£10&nbsp;m boost for Titian masterpiece |accessdate=2008-11-19 |date=19 November 2008 |publisher=[[BBC News]] }}</ref> From 22 October to 14 December 2008<ref>Originally running until 30 November, the exhibition was extended by public demand on 19 November.</ref> it was put on display in Room 1 of the [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] in London to aid the public appeal – the only other painting in this temporary exhibition was the related ''[[The Death of Actaeon]]'' from the London National Gallery's collection, and they were illustrated by the relevant passages from Book 3 of [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]'' in the [[John Dryden]] translation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/oct/23/art-titian-diana-actaeon|title=£50&nbsp;m appeal: Artists back bid to save Titian for nation|first=Charlotte|last=Higgins|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 October 2008|accessdate=29 October 2008 | location=London}}</ref>
Speculation began when the original 31 December deadline passed without definite news and the Scottish Government's announcement of a contribution of £17.5 million in January 2009 triggered a political row, with [[Ian Davidson (Scottish politician)|Ian Davidson]] questioning the deal at a time of [[Financial crisis of 2007–2010|economic hardship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7811408.stm|title= Titian work sparks political row |date=5 January 2009|work=BBC News}}</ref> There was also controversy over attempts to dilute the guarantee that the duke would sell no other of the paintings from the Sutherland Loan should the two Titians be bought.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2009/jan/28/art|title=Behind-the-scenes wrangling with the duke delays Titian announcement|first=Charlotte|last=Higgins|date=28 January 2009|work=The Guardian | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/dec/29/tax-breaks-art-loans-titian|title=Fatal flaw: why masterpieces on loan could be lost to the nation|date=29 December 2009|work=The Guardian|first=Maev|last=Kennedy | location=London}}</ref> However, on 2 February 2009 it was announced that, thanks to the deadline being extended to raise more funds and finalise the payment plan for ''Diana and Callisto'', the £50&nbsp;million had been raised and ''Diana and Actaeon'' would be acquired.<ref name="Funds secured for Titian painting">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7863635.stm|title=Funds secured for Titian painting|work=BBC News|date=2 February 2009}}</ref> The final sum was made up of £12.5&nbsp;million from the Scottish Government, £7.4&nbsp;million from public donations, £12.5&nbsp;million from the National Galleries in London, £10&nbsp;million from the National Heritage Memorial Fund, £2&nbsp;million from the Monument Trust, £4.6&nbsp;million from the National Galleries of Scotland and £1&nbsp;million was secured from the Art Fund.<ref name="Funds secured for Titian painting"/> ''Diana and Actaeon'' will thus be displayed in Scotland for five years, then in London alongside ''The Death of Actaeon'' for five years, on an alternating basis.
